[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1936-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1936 throughout the world.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1936-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per Seamheads.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1936-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams existed that were not part of the Negro National League.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1937-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1937 throughout the world.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1937-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams existed that were not part of either established leagues.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1939-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1939 throughout the world.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1939-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1939-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1940 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the eighth playing of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 9, 1940, at Sportsman's Park in St.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis, Missouri, the home of both the St.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Cardinals of the National League (who were the designated host team) and the St.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the National League defeating the American League 4–0.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Reardon and Basil swapped positions, also Pipgras and Stewart swapped positions.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1942-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1942 throughout the world.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1942-in-baseball-p01] The Negro American League All Star team & Cincinnati Clowns played against the two leagues.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1943-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1943 throughout the world.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1943-in-baseball-p01] This was the seventh season of the Negro American League.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1943-in-baseball-p01] Birmingham and Chicago each won a half of the season, which therefore matched them up in a matchup to determine the champion for the NAL pennant to determine who would make the 1943 Negro World Series.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1943-in-baseball-p01] Birmingham prevailed in five games to win their first ever pennant.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1943-in-baseball-p01] This was the eleventh season of the second Negro National League.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1943-in-baseball-p01] For the sixth time in seven seasons, the Homestead Grays won the pennant, this time under manager Candy Jim Taylor.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1943-in-baseball-p01] The Negro National League All Star team & Atlanta Black Crackers played against the two leagues.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1944 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 12th playing of the "Midsummer Classic" between Major League Baseball's American League (AL) and National League (NL) All-Star teams.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The All-Star Game was held on July 11, 1944 at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, the home of the NL's Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the National League defeating the American League 7–1.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Played during World War II, receipts from the game were distributed to a fund that provided baseball equipment to members of the armed services.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The Pirates hosted the game and were well-represented.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Pirates pitcher Rip Sewell, infielder Bob Elliott, and outfielder Vince DiMaggio were selected for the National League All-Star squad.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Pirates pitchers Max Butcher and Cookie Cuccurullo were named the NL's batting practice pitchers and Pirates catcher Spud Davis was the NL's batting practice catcher.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Honus Wagner was named an honorary coach, the first time this honor was bestowed in Major League Baseball's All-Star Game.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Barr and Hubbard swapped positions, also Berry and Sears swapped positions.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League scored in the second inning on a single by Hank Borowy, its pitcher, but never scored again.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The National League got four runs in the fifth inning, led by Bill Nicholson's pinch-hit double.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Whitey Kurowski knocked in two more runs with a double in the seventh.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] A sacrifice fly by Stan Musial in the eighth inning closed out the scoring.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/1944-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ken Raffensberger was the winning pitcher for the Nationals.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] Born in Pittsburgh, Miller made his Major League debut with the Cincinnati Reds in 1936 as a 19-year-old.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] He played in 41 games over 2 seasons with the Reds before being traded to the New York Yankees in 1938 in exchange for Willard Hershberger.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] Miller never played for the Yankees at the major league level and was subsequently traded to the Boston Bees less than a year later.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] He became the starting shortstop while in Boston, and established himself as one of the National League's best shortstops during his four seasons there.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] His first season with Boston was shortened when he fractured his ankle in a collision with Al Simmons.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] He recovered in 1940 to a career-best .276 for the Bees while leading all NL shortstops in fielding percentage and appearing in the MLB All-Star Game.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] While his batting average fell over the next two seasons with Boston, he led all shortstops in fielding percentage both years.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] He was an All-Star in 1941 and was named as a starter in the All-Star Game in 1942.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] After the 1942 season, he was traded back to the Reds in exchange for Eddie Joost and Nate Andrews.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] He spent five seasons as the Reds' starting shortstop and earned four more selections to the All-Star Game while with the club.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] He continued to play solid defense while with Cincinnati, and he led all shortstops in fielding on two further occasions.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] His final year with the Reds was one of his better seasons as a hitter, as he led the league in doubles and was among the top 10 in home runs and runs batted in.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] He was traded to the Philadelphia Phillies for Johnny Wyrostek before the start of the 1948 season.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] Miller served as the Phillies' shortstop in 1948 but moved to second base in 1949 when he swapped positions with Granny Hamner.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] After two average seasons with Philadelphia, he was acquired by the St.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] Louis Cardinals for the 1950 season, his last in the majors.
[src:eddie-miller-infielder/eddie-miller-infielder] Miller died in 1997 in Lake Worth, Florida.
